WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
My name is Jeroen Ooms.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:18.219
If you don't know me, I'm part of the rOpenSci group at UC Berkeley.

00:00:18.219 --> 00:00:21.559
This is our team.

00:00:21.559 --> 00:00:30.240
And I maintain a lot of R packages, many of them wrapping external libraries, external

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:33.160
C and C++ libraries.

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:44.520
And in addition, I'm also the maintainer of the Windows installers for R base and Rtools.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:49.959
And the current talk will be on the intersection of these two things.

00:00:49.959 --> 00:00:58.080
And I will go into what's involved with building R on Windows, and in particular, how we're

00:00:58.080 --> 00:01:04.320
going to try to improve that for the next generation of the compiler tool chain.

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:05.800
All right.

00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:12.360
So first I'm going to explain a little bit about how it currently works and how Rtools

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:13.360
currently works.

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:21.559
And then in the second part, I'll introduce the new tool chain, which is currently experimental

00:01:21.559 --> 00:01:27.059
in which we're beta testing, hopefully to be included with the next major release of

00:01:27.059 --> 00:01:30.059
R.

00:01:30.059 --> 00:01:31.059
So what's Rtools?

00:01:31.059 --> 00:01:34.400
Well, to understand that, you need to take a step back.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:42.860
So in order to compile things, both base R as well as packages, you need a compiler.

00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:47.580
And on Linux and Mac OS, there is a native compiler on the system.

00:01:47.580 --> 00:01:48.580
Linux is usually GCC.

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:53.459
And on Mac OS, we have Clang with Xcode.

00:01:53.459 --> 00:01:56.580
But on Windows, there's no such thing.

00:01:56.580 --> 00:02:02.860
So on Windows, we need to provide our own compiler tool chain.

00:02:02.860 --> 00:02:05.820
And that is Rtools.

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:11.259
So Rtools, if you've ever had to install a package from source or Windows, it's this

00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:16.699
thing you install separately.

00:02:16.699 --> 00:02:22.380
And it helps you with building stuff on Windows.

00:02:22.380 --> 00:02:25.619
There's no timer, but that's all right.

00:02:25.619 --> 00:02:26.619
All right.

00:02:26.619 --> 00:02:29.300
So Rtools has been around for quite a while.

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:31.300
I didn't invent this.

00:02:31.300 --> 00:02:40.460
As you can see from this retro 90s homepage on CRAN, it has an archive of all of the Rtools

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:42.779
going back like a decade or two.

00:02:42.779 --> 00:02:47.779
So this is something that's been supported for quite a while.

00:02:47.779 --> 00:02:51.820
And I've only taken over on maintenance last year.

00:02:51.820 --> 00:02:57.899
So please don't blame me for everything that's suboptimal.

00:02:57.899 --> 00:03:00.100
So what does the workflow look like?

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:02.259
So you install this thing.

00:03:02.259 --> 00:03:04.619
And then you have this installation dialog.

00:03:04.619 --> 00:03:07.860
And you can choose which components you want to install.

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:13.059
So there's the tool chains, which are like the most important thing.

00:03:13.059 --> 00:03:19.699
Some build utilities, mostly make and shell and tar to extract stuff, which are also needed

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:21.740
to install R packages.

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:24.220
And then the other things are sort of optional.

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:29.220
The last thing is only needed if you want to build R itself, which you should never

00:03:29.220 --> 00:03:30.220
do.

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:34.940
But it's like clip ICU and tech info and tcltk.

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:43.699
All right, so this is what I just said.

00:03:43.699 --> 00:03:55.419
And so to summarize, Rtools is needed to build base R. And if you want to build R packages

00:03:55.539 --> 00:04:02.539
on Windows, which contain C or C++ or Fortran code, and this is the part that most users

00:04:03.059 --> 00:04:04.899
are familiar with.

00:04:04.899 --> 00:04:10.699
But then there's also a very big third thing, which is external libraries.

00:04:10.699 --> 00:04:17.700
So a lot of both base R and a lot of R packages are using external system libraries.

00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:25.420
And those system libraries need to be compiled with the same tool chain and same configuration

00:04:25.779 --> 00:04:32.779
as we're using for base R. And that is sort of a dark piece of the ecosystem right now.

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:37.459
So if you've seen any of my previous talks, you've maybe seen this picture.

00:04:37.459 --> 00:04:40.339
So this is what the dependency system looks like.

00:04:40.339 --> 00:04:46.420
You have all of your packages, and they depend on R. And R itself depends on a lot of external

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:52.420
libraries that we all need to build with the same tool chain in order to build R for Windows.

00:04:52.420 --> 00:04:57.859
And many R packages, they also depend on a bunch of other external libraries.

00:04:57.859 --> 00:05:04.859
And this is a lot of work to build all these things.

00:05:05.899 --> 00:05:11.100
So currently we're doing this manually.

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:18.100
So there's our WinLib organization in which we manually release binaries for the most

00:05:24.739 --> 00:05:31.739
important external C and C++ libraries, which are used by CRAN packages.

00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:38.660
And there's currently, as you can see there, there's 73 libraries in there right now.

00:05:38.779 --> 00:05:40.100
But that's not counting dependencies.

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:46.660
So for example, one of these libraries can depend on a dozen more other sub-libraries.

00:05:46.660 --> 00:05:53.660
So there's like hundreds of external libraries that are in there.

00:05:54.899 --> 00:06:00.660
And this is kind of suboptimal.

00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:04.500
Maintaining these builds is a lot of work.

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:09.700
If you want to build an R package that needs any of these libraries, it's kind of a bit

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:14.779
of a hack, because the package author or the build server would need to manually download

00:06:14.779 --> 00:06:21.100
these libs and then put them in a special location and then mingle with the compiler

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:25.579
and the linker flags on your system, or you can have a script in your package that automatically

00:06:25.579 --> 00:06:26.579
downloads them.

00:06:26.579 --> 00:06:30.660
But it's not the way the world's supposed to work.

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:37.660
So for the next R tools, I wanted to sort of improve the situation, and I've looked

00:06:38.260 --> 00:06:42.940
around a bit and how this is done in other places.

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:49.940
So we want to take advantage of a proper build system, so that we can more easily build all

00:06:53.500 --> 00:07:00.500
of these external libraries using the same compiler toolchain and the same R tool system

00:07:00.779 --> 00:07:07.779
as we use to build R packages or base R itself, and then we want to automate that build process.

00:07:09.739 --> 00:07:16.739
And also, I would like to open and collaboratively maintain these package build scripts, so that

00:07:22.019 --> 00:07:27.940
it's more easy for other people to contribute a build script of a new external package if

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:31.739
they want to use it in their R package.

00:07:31.739 --> 00:07:35.660
So that is sort of the goal of R tools 4.0.

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:39.140
And I want to emphasize again that this is something that we're currently beta testing.

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:46.140
It's not sure at all if and when it's going to ship, but hopefully it will, maybe for

00:07:46.339 --> 00:07:52.059
the upcoming release or otherwise the one after that.

00:07:52.059 --> 00:07:53.459
So you can already test it.

00:07:53.459 --> 00:07:59.179
If you go to CRAN on Google R tools 4.0, there's a special page, and there you can

00:07:59.179 --> 00:08:06.179
install R tools 4.0 for your system, and then there's also a special version of R, which

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:14.779
I call R testing, and it's like the R devel builds, if you've ever tried this, but it

00:08:14.779 --> 00:08:21.779
has been configured to use this new toolchain, so it's sort of hardcoded the path to the

00:08:22.779 --> 00:08:29.779
new toolchain, and it has a custom location where it installs the packages, so you can

00:08:31.179 --> 00:08:37.820
use this, you can install this, and you can play with the new R tools, and it won't conflict

00:08:37.820 --> 00:08:44.820
with any other package libraries or so that are using the current stable toolchain.

00:08:45.820 --> 00:08:52.820
So what's the experience like? You install this thing, and then suddenly in your start

00:08:53.299 --> 00:08:58.140
menu there's this new thing, which wasn't there before, because before R tools was just

00:08:58.140 --> 00:09:03.539
sort of a bundle that you install over in system, and now there's actually a shell,

00:09:03.539 --> 00:09:07.820
and there's a thing, so you're like, what if I click on that?

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:13.820
So if you click on that, it opens a terminal window, so R tools now actually includes a

00:09:13.820 --> 00:09:20.820
full terminal with Bash, a shell, and all of the tools that you're used to, or probably

00:09:24.539 --> 00:09:31.539
not if you're on Windows, but it's a full Unix-like environment based on MSYS2 and Sequin,

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:38.940
which has all of the build tools that you need to build all of these open source libraries.

00:09:39.940 --> 00:09:46.940
So what's in the tin? Well, the most important thing is there's a nice terminal, and there's

00:09:47.619 --> 00:09:52.900
the shell and everything that comes with that, Bash, and then there's all of these utilities

00:09:52.900 --> 00:09:57.659
which are part of Sequin, like Make and Set and Perl and whatnot.

00:09:57.659 --> 00:10:03.619
And of course there's the compilers, there's the MinGW compilers, one for 32-bit and one

00:10:03.619 --> 00:10:08.859
for 64-bit Windows. But the most important thing in new R tools is there's a package

00:10:08.859 --> 00:10:15.859
manager, and there's a real package manager to build and install external libraries, just

00:10:16.140 --> 00:10:23.140
like apt on Debian or yum on Enterprise Linux, or homebrew on OSX.

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:31.140
So what would that look like? The package manager is called pacman, and then the first

00:10:38.340 --> 00:10:45.340
command, pacman does s, stands for sync, and then y is it syncs with the repository index,

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:52.619
and for example, syu would upgrade all of the installed packages, and then the second

00:10:52.619 --> 00:10:58.179
block of code shows, for example, how you would install the libxml2 package.

00:10:58.179 --> 00:11:04.380
And in pacman, there's a separate package for the 32-bit and the 64-bit package, but

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:09.859
you can install them both with this syntax. And I want to emphasize, I didn't invent pacman,

00:11:09.859 --> 00:11:16.099
this is the package manager from R Linux, which has been ported to Windows, and it's

00:11:16.099 --> 00:11:23.099
a really nice fit, and it's really nice. It has all of the features that you can expect

00:11:24.539 --> 00:11:31.539
from a modern package manager, so it really starts to feel like a proper operating system.

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:39.340
So, I didn't have the confidence to do a live demo like Gabor, so what does that look like?

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:48.940
There's a shell, and then this is pacman, and if you do pacman s y, it updates the repository,

00:11:52.460 --> 00:11:57.859
and here I'm installing the curl package, and it says, you know, curl depends on libssh

00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:04.179
and openshell, so we need these things as well, so it starts pulling in these things,

00:12:04.179 --> 00:12:11.179
and then it's installing, blah, blah, blah, and then this is for speed, so it's slower

00:12:12.179 --> 00:12:16.739
in real time, and then it's done, right? And now it's there. So now you can do package

00:12:16.739 --> 00:12:23.739
config curl, and it's there. So it's really like you would expect from, you know, from

00:12:24.739 --> 00:12:31.739
app.yaml or so. All right, so which packages do we have?

00:12:31.859 --> 00:12:38.419
So there's a repository under r-windows, rtools packages, which currently contains all of

00:12:38.419 --> 00:12:45.419
the, like, I think about 100 packages that I've ordered to this system, so this repository

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:51.900
contains all of the build formulas for this package, or not the actual binaries, but these

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:58.940
are like the pacman config file to build these things, and if you look what's in there, every

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:09.500
of these subdirectories contains a file called package build, and this defines the name of

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:16.500
the package, like the URL of the source, you know, a bunch of patches, checksums and stuff,

00:13:16.940 --> 00:13:20.940
and, you know, what's needed to build the package and install the package, so usually

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:27.940
there's like some CMake or a configure line and then make and then make install.

00:13:30.619 --> 00:13:35.140
So what does that look like? So, for example, here's an example where they're building the

00:13:35.140 --> 00:13:42.140
popular package, which uses CMake to build, you always have to do make package, MGW, so

00:13:46.580 --> 00:13:52.500
if you do that in the directory that contains this package build file, like, everything

00:13:52.500 --> 00:13:59.500
else is automatically done, so it starts pulling in the source for the popular library, it

00:13:59.859 --> 00:14:06.859
runs CMake on all of these things, and you get the output, and then, you know, if everything

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:14.780
works, in the end, it will compress libraries, strip out some debug symbols, and create an

00:14:15.780 --> 00:14:22.780
actual package, which is a tar.xc file. So let's run, and here it's done, and now it's

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:34.260
sort of tidying up the install, stripping, loads, and then you have an actual R package,

00:14:34.419 --> 00:14:41.419
and the binary package is this new tar.xc file that was created, right, so it's once

00:14:42.419 --> 00:14:48.900
the formula is in place, like, maintaining these things is hopefully going to be much

00:14:48.900 --> 00:14:55.500
easier than it is now. All right, so that is how you would do it manually, but of course

00:14:55.500 --> 00:15:02.500
you want to automate it, so if you send a pull request to this library, or in my case,

00:15:03.179 --> 00:15:09.299
if you push straight to the master branch, AppVeyor will start building these things,

00:15:09.299 --> 00:15:16.299
and they look like this, and you can use, you can look at, in the log file of the AppVeyor,

00:15:17.659 --> 00:15:24.659
which are the latest things that you've built, and this is sort of the most beautiful part

00:15:28.179 --> 00:15:35.179
of the system, so it automatically deploys, so if you look in the AppVeyor log file, towards

00:15:36.179 --> 00:15:43.179
the end, and if it's in a pull request or a branch, it will then just say it was complete,

00:15:44.059 --> 00:15:49.099
but if you're in the master branch, it will then automatically deploy everything to Bintray,

00:15:49.099 --> 00:15:56.099
so all of these, all of the binaries for these Windows packages, they are hosted on Bintray,

00:15:56.140 --> 00:16:03.140
and they are automatically deployed once the build is successful from AppVeyor, so there's

00:16:04.140 --> 00:16:09.219
nothing that I have to do other than merging the pull request to actually release these

00:16:09.219 --> 00:16:15.340
libraries, right, so once the build is complete, at the bottom here you see it's, AppVeyor

00:16:15.340 --> 00:16:20.820
starts uploading the binaries to Bintray, and it's sort of recalculating the index file,

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:27.820
and then you can see it on this URL, so this is the URL where all of the binary packages

00:16:28.820 --> 00:16:35.820
are stored, and this is the URL that then Pacman, in our tools, uses to grab the packages,

00:16:38.419 --> 00:16:43.580
so it's live immediately, there's no manual step anymore, you know, you send the pull

00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:49.260
request, AppVeyor builds, if it succeeds, it deploys on Bintray, and then the next time

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:55.099
any user would do Pacman as update, it starts pulling in these new libraries, so it sort

00:16:55.099 --> 00:17:02.099
of ties up the circle really nicely. Yeah, so I hope that this will make the maintenance

00:17:06.859 --> 00:17:13.859
much easier, and I should emphasize that once you have installed one of these system libraries

00:17:17.939 --> 00:17:23.939
using Pacman, our tools will automatically find it when you build an R package that needs

00:17:23.979 --> 00:17:29.859
a library, so there's no need to set special compiler flags or special linker flags to

00:17:29.859 --> 00:17:36.219
point to a particular location, because Pacman installs it exactly where the linker expects

00:17:36.219 --> 00:17:41.300
to find it, and where the compiler expects to find it, right, so it's going to feel much

00:17:41.300 --> 00:17:47.140
more like apt, or yum, or brew, where if you need a system dependency, you do the Pacman

00:17:47.140 --> 00:17:51.500
install, and the system dependency is there, and then your R package should just build

00:17:51.500 --> 00:17:58.500
without any further hacking. So, in summary, last slide, the new version of R tools will

00:18:01.219 --> 00:18:08.219
include a proper build environment that will make it easier for me, for us, to build and

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:17.900
install all of the external libraries. Pacman makes it really nice to package and distribute

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:25.900
and install these libs, so there's no manual copying of files anymore on build server.

00:18:26.459 --> 00:18:33.459
R will then automatically find those installed libs, so you don't need to pass special linker

00:18:34.300 --> 00:18:40.699
flags or include flags when you're installing an R package on Windows from source, and the

00:18:40.699 --> 00:18:45.540
most important part is that, you know, these libraries are all going to be transparent

00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:52.540
and reproducible and automated via the CI, so there should be much less maintenance,

00:18:53.099 --> 00:18:56.660
but also I think there's going to be a bit more accountability, because currently, you

00:18:56.660 --> 00:19:01.739
know, I'm just uploading these binaries to R winlib, but, you know, nobody knows how

00:19:01.739 --> 00:19:08.739
they are built and, you know, what I put in there, and, like, this system is going to

00:19:09.459 --> 00:19:16.459
be fully open, fully transparent, fully automated, and everything gets built in a public place

00:19:16.859 --> 00:19:23.859
and deployed, and, you know, everyone can contribute, so, yeah, that's it. Here are

00:19:24.660 --> 00:19:31.660
all the slides below. Thanks.

00:19:34.060 --> 00:19:38.060
Thank you very much, Jeroen, for your talk and also for making my life as a Windows user

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:45.140
so much easier than it otherwise has been. We have time for one question. This question

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:49.140
at the back, I think it's Rich here with the golden shirt.

00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:56.140
Thanks. Good throw. So this sounds like it makes it a lot easier to have more external

00:19:56.859 --> 00:20:03.859
dependencies, so are there going to be some new dependencies that R uses?

00:20:04.859 --> 00:20:11.859
So, because it's now easier to have external dependencies for R, are there going to be

00:20:17.099 --> 00:20:22.579
some more dependencies in base R? Exciting new tools.

00:20:22.579 --> 00:20:29.579
Yes, so I hope that this system will make it easier to use, to take advantage of these

00:20:30.579 --> 00:20:37.579
external libraries in R more easily, because previously you're sort of tied to what I mean

00:20:37.579 --> 00:20:42.579
on Linux and Fedora, most of it is available, but on Windows, the system was really limited

00:20:42.579 --> 00:20:48.579
by, you know, people that were willing to build these things for you, and there's, like,

00:20:48.579 --> 00:20:55.579
only two of them that would probably do that, so I hope that this will, I hope not open

00:20:56.140 --> 00:21:03.140
the floodgates, but at least give R users better access to up-to-date high-quality libraries

00:21:08.619 --> 00:21:10.339
that now also work on Windows.

